                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d319">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/6229: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-04-26T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >April 26, 1933—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 26—7:37 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>377. Department’s 133, April 25, and my 369, April 25, 11 p.m. I saw my British
                    colleague this morning and we are agreed that situation revealed by statements
                    of Chiang Monlin as reported in my 357, April 22, 8 p.m., and more recent
                    statement of Vice Minister Liu indicate lack of agreement between Wang Ching-wei
                    and Foreign Office authorities and we, therefore, propose to do nothing further
                    in this matter. Before doing anything myself I shall, of course, inform
                    Department and obtain its approval.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
